{"id":"1608.00458","submitter":"Alessio Spurio Mancini","authors":"Alberto Bailoni, Alessio Spurio Mancini and Luca Amendola","title":"Improving Fisher matrix forecasts for galaxy surveys: window function,\n  bin cross-correlation, and bin redshift uncertainty","comments":"Accepted for publication in MNRAS","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1093/mnras/stx1209","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Fisher matrix is a widely used tool to forecast the performance of future\nexperiments and approximate the likelihood of large data sets. Most of the\nforecasts for cosmological parameters in galaxy clustering studies rely on the\nFisher matrix approach for large-scale experiments like DES, Euclid, or SKA.\nHere we improve upon the standard method by taking into account three effects:\nthe finite window function, the correlation between redshift bins, and the\nuncertainty on the bin redshift. The first two effects are negligible only in\nthe limit of infinite surveys. The third effect, on the contrary, is negligible\nfor infinitely small bins. Here we show how to take into account these effects\nand what the impact on forecasts of a Euclid-type experiment will be. The main\nresult of this article is that the windowing and the bin cross-correlation\ninduce a considerable change in the forecasted errors, of the order of 10-30%\nfor most cosmological parameters, while the redshift bin uncertainty can be\nneglected for bins smaller than $\\Delta z = 0.1$ roughly.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 1 Aug 2016 14:52:41 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Dec 2016 10:13:09 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 15 May 2017 22:09:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-06-28"}
